# Research: YouTube Content on LLM Wiki / Company Brain / Agent Memory / Knowledge Layers

## Summary

YouTube content on "LLM wiki / company brain" converges on three dominant architectures: (1) **file-system/Markdown wikis** (Karpathy's LLM Wiki, LangChain OpenWiki, Harrison Chase's "Deep Agents" harness) where knowledge lives as version-controlled Markdown with no database; (2) **graph-based memory** (Microsoft GraphRAG, LightRAG, Zep/Graphiti, Cognee) where entity-relationship graphs enable multi-hop reasoning that vector RAG cannot do; and (3) **stateful agent memory tiers** (Letta/MemGPT, Mem0, LangMem) with hierarchical memory blocks (core/archival/recall or semantic/episodic/procedural). The most-cited pain point across ALL videos is **context window pollution/bloat** — raw history or naive RAG chunks fill the context with noise, degrading reasoning. The second most-cited pain point is **knowledge staleness/rot** — documentation and memories become obsolete without automated maintenance. MongoDB is almost never mentioned by name; when database backends are discussed, PostgreSQL (with pgvector) and Neo4j dominate. Where MongoDB is implicitly contrasted, it's characterized as a "single typology" document store that excels at similarity search but lacks structural reasoning and multi-hop traversal.

---

## Findings

### 1. The Karpathy "LLM Wiki" Pattern — File-Based, Compounding Knowledge

**Video:** "Karpathy's LLM Wiki - Full Setup Guide" — community tutorial channel
**URL:** https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4SB3T1reCHw

- **Architecture:** Three-layer model: (1) Sources (immutable raw inputs — PDFs, transcripts), (2) Wiki (AI-compiled Markdown pages with `[[Wiki-links]]`), (3) Schema (`CLAUDE.md` defining page types and maintenance rules).
- **Data Model:** Graph-based on top of Markdown files. Wiki-links create an interconnected network. Each new source "explodes" into 5-15 wiki pages with cross-references.
- **Storage Backend:** Local-first — Obsidian as frontend, local file system as database. No cloud database.
- **Biggest Pain Point:** "Knowledge Evaporation" — traditional RAG starts from zero every session; knowledge doesn't compound.
- **Solution:** "Compilation" metaphor (like a software compiler). LLM compiles raw docs into structured wiki, updates existing pages, flags contradictions. `--save` flag auto-saves synthesis answers as new wiki pages. "Lint" operation checks for orphaned pages, broken references, contradictions.
- **MongoDB:** Not mentioned. Contrasted with "Traditional RAG / Enterprise Knowledge Bases" as stateless search vs. stateful compounding knowledge.

### 2. LangChain OpenWiki — Git-Native Agent Documentation

**Video:** "Stop Feeding Your Whole Repo to AI, OpenWiki Fixes Context" — Prism Labs
**URL:** https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=GwyLSG_e5lw

**Video:** "OpenWiki: The Hidden AI Agent Tool Nobody Uses [2026]"
**URL:** https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4s24K3BQYHo

**Video:** "OpenWiki CLI Tutorial" — RayCodes
**URL:** https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7mjUFTi-ZyA

**Video:** "OpenWiki + WikiStream Local Setup"
**URL:** https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Pz_UcC3BwXY

- **Architecture:** CLI tool (TypeScript) that scans codebase, generates structured Markdown docs, and wires them into `AGENTS.md`/`CLAUDE.md` instruction files. GitHub Actions automation loop for daily updates. Dual-track system: human docs (narrative) + machine docs (structured, ambiguity-free).
- **Data Model:** Hierarchical Markdown wiki (`overview.md`, `architecture.md`, `api.md`, `quickstart.md` as central index). Described as a "dense, interconnected knowledge graph" in one video. Git-diff aware — only updates affected pages.
- **Storage Backend:** File-based, Git-native. Docs stored in `openwiki/` folder within repository. Version-controlled alongside code. Enterprise: LiteLLM proxy support for internal gateways. Config/credentials in `~/.openwiki/.env`.
- **Biggest Pain Point:** Documentation Rot — hand-written docs become stale immediately. Also Context Window Bloat from monolithic instruction files.
- **Solution:** Git-diff awareness (analyzes commit diffs to update only affected pages). CI/CD automation with cryptographic hash checksums (skips if no changes). PR-based workflow for human review of AI-generated docs.
- **MongoDB:** Not mentioned. Contrasted with centralized database-backed RAG — decentralized, repo-local Markdown vs. external database with connection strings.

### 3. Harrison Chase (LangChain) — "Deep Agents" Harness & File-System Memory

**Video:** Harrison Chase talk on agent architecture (Deep Agents / harness)
**URL:** https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=rSKh6bVuVZI

**Video:** "Your Harness, Your Memory" — Harrison Chase
**URL:** https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=fmGFI91XWs8

**Video:** Harrison Chase on Latent Space podcast (traces, context engineering)
**URL:** https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Ouv5Be-hulY

**Video:** "Long-Term Agentic Memory with LangGraph" (DeepLearning.AI)
**URL:** https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9E1e3ZW3-pw

- **Architecture:** "Harness" (scaffolding) surrounding the LLM. Core components: detailed system prompts, planning tools, sub-agents, file system interface. "Deep Agents" framework with skills (markdown `skill.md` files) + memory (short-term checkpointed, long-term semantic/episodic/procedural).
- **Data Model:** Skills as curated markdown folders. Memory segmented into Semantic (facts), Episodic (past interactions), Procedural (instructions as files). Progressive disclosure — only loads skill details when matched to task.
- **Storage Backend:** File-system interface (real or virtual). Chase explicitly argues LLMs are "natively great at working with filesystems." Physical storage can be SQL, S3, or local disk, but exposed as a filesystem. Virtual file system might be backed by Postgres for scalability.
- **Biggest Pain Point:** (1) Communication/handoffs between main agent and sub-agents. (2) Context bloat — raw history fills context window. (3) Memory lock-in — proprietary boundaries trap agent experience.
- **Solution:** Context compaction (summarization at 80% threshold). Offloading raw history to filesystem. Open-source, model-agnostic harness with transparent file-system memory for portability. "Sleep-time compute" — agents review traces overnight to self-improve.
- **MongoDB:** Not mentioned. Contrast is file-system-first vs. database-API-first — Chase argues LLMs reason better through directories/files than through database query APIs.

### 4. Letta/MemGPT (Charles Packer) — LLM OS with Hierarchical Memory

**Video:** "Letta: Building Stateful AI Agents with Memory" — Charles Packer
**URL:** https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=sgD-sw0RW78

**Video:** "Stateful Agents — Full Workshop with Charles Packer"
**URL:** https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=E0k9Ppq6yXY

**Video:** "MemGPT: Giving AI Infinite Memory (Humans of AI)"
**URL:** https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4aOLxPdx1Dg

- **Architecture:** "LLM OS" / "ChatOS" — treats LLM context window as RAM, external storage as disk. Decoupled tiers: State (memory context), Model (reasoning engine), Action (tools/MCP). Server-client architecture (Letta Server with FastAPI). Agent uses function calling to manage its own memory.
- **Data Model:** Memory hierarchy — Core Memory (in context window: "human" block + "persona" block, self-editable), Archival Memory (infinite external store for large docs), Recall Memory (complete interaction log). "Paging" abstraction from OS design. Scratchpad/working memory for notes-to-self.
- **Storage Backend:** PostgreSQL (production), SQLite (simple setups). Flexible for MemGPT: SQL databases, text files, vector databases (Faiss).
- **Biggest Pain Point:** (1) Inherent statelessness of LLMs — no natural memory formation. (2) "Context Derailment/Pollution" — context becomes too long, cluttered with atomic facts, eventually "goes haywire." (3) Limited context window for company-scale knowledge.
- **Solution:** (1) LLM OS with "context compilation" — automates fetching relevant info from external DB into context window. Agent given tools (`core_memory_replace`, `archival_memory_search`) to self-edit memory. (2) "Sleep-time Compute" — asynchronous background cycles where agent rewrites memory state, consolidating messy raw history into structured "Learned Context." (3) Iterative retrieval (can rephrase and re-search, unlike one-shot RAG).
- **MongoDB:** Not mentioned by name. Contrast is with "stateless" / "middleware" approaches where data is dumped into context window. Packer argues persistent state (in PostgreSQL) is the true proprietary value — models are interchangeable, memory is the moat.

### 5. Mem0 — Fact Extraction Memory Layer

**Video:** "Mem0: Building AI Agents with Scalable Long-Term Memory" (Arize AI)
**URL:** https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=nXygWVJj_1A

- **Architecture:** Memory layer between agent and LLM. Interception loop: (1) Extract — passes interaction through extraction LLM to distill facts, (2) Inject — searches memory and injects only relevant facts into system prompt. Memory lifecycle: Add/Extract → Consolidate/Update (belief revision for contradictions) → Search/Retrieve → Inject.
- **Data Model:** "Fact Gems" — discrete distilled facts (e.g., "user is vegetarian"). User-scoped (`user_id`). Metadata/timestamps for temporal pruning. Three levels: User-level, Session-level, Agent-level.
- **Storage Backend:** Vector Store (embeddings for semantic search). Often hybrid: vector DB (Qdrant/Pinecone) + knowledge graph (Neo4j).
- **Biggest Pain Point:** "Context Stuffing" — naive fix of prepending entire conversation history. Fails via: (1) linear cost scaling, (2) relevance collapse (irrelevant old data crowds out current needs), (3) context limit ceiling with quality degradation before limit.
- **Solution:** Selective long-term memory — extract facts, use vector store to inject only what's relevant. Reduces token usage by up to 90%.
- **MongoDB:** Not mentioned. Contrasted with raw JSON blob storage of chat history — Mem0 stores distilled facts, not raw transcripts. Document retrieval vs. semantic retrieval.

### 6. Zep/Graphiti — Temporal Knowledge Graph for Agent Memory

**Video:** "Zep: A Temporal Knowledge Graph Architecture for Agent Memory" (KGC)
**URL:** https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2V-zMRF7lL0

- **Architecture:** Zep memory layer service + Graphiti engine (dynamic, temporal-aware knowledge graph). Uses "Reflection" technique — LLM double-checks entity extractions to minimize hallucinations. Retrieval pipeline: Search (conceptual + keyword + graph BFS) → Re-rank (RRF/MMR) → Construct (structured text for LLM).
- **Data Model:** Three-tiered hierarchical knowledge graph: (1) Episode Subgraph (raw input messages, non-lossy log), (2) Semantic Entity Subgraph (extracted entities + relationships, entity resolution), (3) Community Subgraph (high-level clusters of connected entities). Bi-temporal model: Event Time (when it happened) + Transactional Time (when ingested). Non-lossy updates — old facts marked "invalidated" with timestamp, not deleted.
- **Storage Backend:** Not explicitly named (likely Neo4j or custom graph store). Bi-temporal storage model.
- **Biggest Pain Point:** Static RAG + context window problem — traditional RAG relies on static documents that don't evolve; LLMs lose thread of long histories or data in constant flux.
- **Solution:** Dynamic updating via Label Propagation Algorithm (updates community structures on the fly). Context efficiency: 1.6k tokens sent to LLM vs. 115k baseline (90% latency reduction, 2.6s vs. 29s). Benchmarks: 94.8% accuracy on DMR (vs. MemGPT 93.4%), 18.5% accuracy improvement on LongMemEval.
- **MongoDB:** Not mentioned. Contrasted with static document stores — document vs. graph model. Zep tracks validity periods for every fact, modeling "when" something was true.

### 7. Cognee — Triple-Storage "Company Brain"

**Video:** Cognee tutorial series — "Build a Company Brain in Python"
**URL:** https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Rnm2BlZU1t0

**Video:** Cognee + Memgraph integration demo
**URL:** https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=w04eZ_ezONM

- **Architecture:** Triple-storage architecture (Relational + Vector + Graph). ECL Pipeline: Extract (pull raw data) → Cognify (LLM identifies entities/relationships) → Load (store in triple-store). Four core operations: `remember()`, `recall()`, `forget()`, `improve()`.
- **Data Model:** Structured ontologies via custom Python classes (override default AI behavior). Baml tool for deterministic JSON formatting before graph insertion. Graph-based relations — facts as nodes in interconnected web. Provenance tracking (who uploaded, from what source, when).
- **Storage Backend:** Hybrid — Relational (immutable ledger for provenance, SQL-like filtering), Vector (semantic similarity), Graph (entities as nodes, relationships as edges, multi-hop reasoning). Self-hosted with single Postgres instance or Cognee Cloud.
- **Biggest Pain Point:** "Contextual Degradation" — in extended/multi-threaded sessions, agents "lose their place." Traditional RAG finds related paragraphs but can't "connect the dots" between disparate facts across sessions.
- **Solution:** Combining vector search with graph store provides structural framework for multi-hop reasoning. Agent maintains cohesive worldview across sessions. `improve()` continuously distills short-term caches into global graph.
- **MongoDB:** Not named. Contrasted with "single database typology" / "standard vector databases" (how many orgs use MongoDB's vector search). Single database finds mathematically similar text but lacks structural reasoning. Triple-store ensures document is linked to agent's historical context AND organization's rules (provenance + ontology).

### 8. Microsoft GraphRAG — Community Detection + Global Summarization

**Video:** "Intro to GraphRAG" (Microsoft Reactor / RAGHack)
**URL:** https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=f6pUqDeMiG0

- **Architecture:** Hybrid retrieval pipeline: indexing (chunk → LLM entity extraction → knowledge graph → community detection → summaries) + retrieval (Vector Search + Graph Querying/Cypher + Global Search using community summaries).
- **Data Model:** Property Graph Model — Nodes (with Labels and Properties), Relationships (with Direction, Type, Properties). Ontology as foundational schema. Community clusters (C0-C3 levels) via Leiden algorithm.
- **Storage Backend:** Neo4j (core graph engine). Enterprise Azure: Azure AI Search (vectors), Azure Blob Storage (raw data), Cosmos DB (metadata/community reports), AKS (API hosting).
- **Biggest Pain Point:** "Baseline RAG" (vector-only) fails on complex multi-hop queries and high-level thematic questions (e.g., "What are the main themes of this 500-page document?"). 72-83% improvement in comprehensiveness vs. baseline.
- **Solution:** LLMs pre-process data into graph. Community Detection groups related nodes. Pre-generated community summaries enable global reasoning across entire dataset. Local Search (specific facts) vs. Global Search (broad themes).
- **MongoDB:** Not named specifically. Contrasted with "Baseline RAG" approaches (including MongoDB Atlas Vector Search) — vector similarity finds text that "looks like" the query; GraphRAG understands relationships. Multi-hop reasoning (3-4 connections away) that document-based approaches miss.

### 9. LightRAG — Cost-Efficient Graph RAG with Incremental Updates

**Video:** "LightRAG: A More Efficient Solution than GraphRAG?" — Prompt Engineering
**URL:** https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=oageL-1I0GE

- **Architecture:** Graph-based indexing with Dual-Level Retrieval: Low-Level (specific entities + attributes), High-Level (broader themes across multiple entities), Hybrid (both). Indexing: chunk → LLM entity/relationship extraction → knowledge graph.
- **Data Model:** Knowledge graph (entities as nodes, relationships as edges). Five query modes: local, global, hybrid, naive, mix.
- **Storage Backend:** Nano Vector Database. Local files: `graph_chunk_entity_relation.graphml`, `kv_store_full_docs.json`, `vdb_entities.json`, `vdb_relationships.json`. Also supports Neo4j, Qdrant, FAISS.
- **Biggest Pain Point:** High cost and inflexibility of Microsoft GraphRAG — requires full graph reconstruction when new data is added, leading to massive token consumption.
- **Solution:** Incremental updates — add new data without rebuilding entire graph. Cost drop from ~$4.00 to ~$0.15 for same dataset. Up to 6,000x cheaper query costs vs. GraphRAG.
- **MongoDB:** Not named. Contrasted with "Naive RAG" (flat chunks in document stores) — MongoDB vector search is good for specific snippets but struggles with global/thematic queries. LightRAG preserves "connective tissue" between documents.

### 10. GraphRAG for Business Intelligence (AI Jason)

**Video:** "Build Knowledge Graph-powered AI Agents" — AI Jason
**URL:** https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=6B29VDvPPzc

- **Architecture:** GraphRAG with vector + knowledge graph. Source documents chunked and embedded into vector store, entities also extracted and connected in graph database.
- **Data Model:** Entity-to-Entity relationships (nodes + edges). Focus on many-to-many relationships (person → subsidiary → parent company → support tickets).
- **Storage Backend:** Amazon Neptune (managed graph database).
- **Biggest Pain Point:** "Headache" of complex joins — in traditional relational or document-based systems, finding deep connections across disparate sources (CRM, support, docs) requires excessive table joins, difficult to write and poor performance at scale.
- **Solution:** Native graph database for multi-hop traversal without join performance penalty. Relationships as "first-class citizens."
- **MongoDB:** Explicitly characterized as "still kind of tabular" / isolated. Document-based approach makes many-to-many traversal cumbersome (relationships nested or referenced within documents). Graph databases prioritize inherent connectivity.

### 11. Cole Medin — Contextual Retrieval with Postgres/pgvector

**Video:** Cole Medin RAG agent architecture tutorial
**URL:** https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=z_LGan-t2Mo

- **Architecture:** RAG with contextual preprocessing. Ingestion (Google Drive → text → chunks) → Preprocessing (LLM adds document-level context to each chunk) → Retrieval Agent (searches vector DB).
- **Data Model:** Chunking (400-800 chars) + Contextualization (low-cost LLM generates 50-100 token context per chunk, prepended before embedding). Final record: `[Context] + [Chunk Text]` + metadata (File ID, Title, Source URL) + vector embedding.
- **Storage Backend:** Postgres-based — Neon and Supabase with `pgvector` extension. Neon highlighted for serverless autoscaling and database branching.
- **Biggest Pain Point:** Standard RAG inaccuracy — individual chunks are "decontextualized." Retrieving a chunk about "revenue growth" without knowing which company/quarter leads to ~10% failure rate.
- **Solution:** Contextual Retrieval (Anthropic strategy) — prepend document-level context to every chunk before embedding. Reduces failure rate to <3%.
- **MongoDB:** Not mentioned. Postgres/pgvector preferred — vector data lives alongside traditional application metadata in ACID-compliant queries.

### 12. "Company Brain" Modular RAG (Postgres vs. MongoDB)

**Video:** Company Brain architecture deep dive
**URL:** https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=NK8tTrZ3jEw

- **Architecture:** Modular RAG — Ingestion (connectors to Slack/Notion/GitHub/Jira), Orchestration (LangChain/LlamaIndex), Retrieval (semantic + keyword hybrid), Agentic Layer (agent decides which tool/DB to query).
- **Data Model:** Hierarchical — chunks + rich metadata (Author, Date, Permission Level, Source URL, Parent Document ID). Graph relationships (GraphRAG) mapping Slack conversation → GitHub PR → Notion doc.
- **Storage Backend:** PostgreSQL with pgvector. Rationale: company brain needs relational joins (vector results + user permissions + document metadata) in a single ACID-compliant query.
- **Biggest Pain Point:** Data staleness & syncing — the ETL pipeline. If employee deletes a Notion page but it stays in vector DB, LLM hallucinates outdated info.
- **Solution:** Event-driven re-indexing via webhooks — incremental updates triggered by source changes, not nightly scrapes.
- **MongoDB:** **Directly contrasted.** MongoDB Atlas Vector Search vs. Postgres/pgvector:
  - MongoDB: Excellent for polymorphic unstructured JSON; eventual consistency can lead to "ghost" data; good "all-in-one" if data already in Mongo; difficult to perform complex joins between vectors and organizational charts.
  - Postgres/pgvector: Better for strict relationships (permissions); strong consistency; better performance for "Filtered Vector Search"; easy to filter vectors by Department/Team ID via SQL joins.
  - **Verdict:** For a Company Brain with complex permissioning, relational-vector hybrid (Postgres) or specialized Knowledge Graph more effective than document-store.

### 13. Agentic File Search (fs-explorer) — Beyond Chunking

**Video:** fs-explorer agentic file search system
**URL:** https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=vtugjs2chdA

- **Architecture:** Three-phase exploration: (1) Parallel Document Scan (1500-char previews), (2) Deep Dive (full extraction of relevant docs), (3) Backtracking (follows cross-references). LlamaIndex Workflow for event-driven loops. Tools: `scan_folder`, `parse_file`, `preview_file`, `read`, `grep`, `glob`.
- **Data Model:** Documents standardized to Markdown via Docling. Consistent format for LLM processing.
- **Storage Backend:** Local filesystem. Persistent key-value cache for document data. No cloud uploads.
- **Biggest Pain Point:** Chunking in standard RAG — causes loss of global document context, cross-document references (e.g., "See Exhibit B"), and document dependencies.
- **Solution:** Agentic search — AI agent reasons and navigates documents like a human (scanning, reasoning, following references) instead of relying on similarity matching of pre-computed embeddings.
- **MongoDB:** Not mentioned. Focus is entirely on local filesystem-based agentic search.

### 14. "YouTube Brain" — Obsidian Vault as Knowledge Graph

**Video:** "YouTube Brain" — Obsidian + agent skill layer
**URL:** https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-79UPXDQ1KI

- **Architecture:** "Obsidian Vault plus agent skill layer." Follows Karpathy's "Hot Index Wiki" approach. Three pillars: Creator Growth, Developer API, Advertising.
- **Data Model:** Knowledge graph of interlinked Markdown files. Source-cited (every claim traced to official source with date). Folders: `research-pack`, `prompts`, `SOPs`.
- **Storage Backend:** Git (GitHub repository). Version-controlled, forkable, collaborative via Pull Requests.
- **Biggest Pain Point:** Relying solely on skills (code) and prompts without grounded, source-cited context leads to hallucinations.
- **Solution:** "Second Brain" (the Vault) — structured, verifiable knowledge base that agents can "cook" from. Performing better than skills and prompts alone.
- **MongoDB:** Not mentioned. Git-based approach has full change history vs. destructive database state changes. Markdown vault is more portable across LLM agents without database connectors.

