## Cross-Cutting Analysis: Most-Cited Pain Points

| Pain Point | Videos Citing | Count |
|---|---|---|
| **Context window pollution/bloat** — raw history or naive RAG chunks fill context with noise | Letta, Mem0, OpenWiki, Harrison Chase, GraphRAG, LightRAG | 6+ |
| **Knowledge staleness/rot** — docs/memories become obsolete without automated maintenance | OpenWiki (all 4 videos), Company Brain Modular RAG, Karpathy Wiki | 6+ |
| **Multi-hop reasoning failure** — vector RAG can't connect facts across documents | GraphRAG, LightRAG, Cognee, Zep/Graphiti, AI Jason | 5+ |
| **LLM statelessness** — no natural memory formation across sessions | Letta/MemGPT (all 3 videos), Mem0, LangMem | 5+ |
| **Decontextualized chunks** — chunks lose document-level context | Cole Medin, fs-explorer, GraphRAG | 3+ |
| **Memory lock-in** — proprietary boundaries trap agent experience | Harrison Chase (Harness video) | 1 |

## Cross-Cutting Analysis: Architecture Patterns

| Pattern | Key Proponents | Storage |
|---|---|---|
| **File-system/Mardown wiki** (no database) | Karpathy, OpenWiki, Harrison Chase "Deep Agents" | Local files, Git, Obsidian |
| **Graph-based memory** (knowledge graph + vectors) | Microsoft GraphRAG, LightRAG, Zep/Graphiti, Cognee, AI Jason | Neo4j, Amazon Neptune, custom graph stores |
| **Stateful agent memory tiers** (hierarchical blocks) | Letta/MemGPT, Mem0, LangMem | PostgreSQL, vector stores, hybrid |
| **Postgres/pgvector hybrid** | Cole Medin, Company Brain Modular RAG | PostgreSQL with pgvector |

## MongoDB Mentions Across YouTube

**Direct mentions:** Essentially **zero** — no YouTube video in this research explicitly names MongoDB as a recommended or primary backend for an LLM wiki/company brain.

**Implicit contrasts (where MongoDB's category is discussed):**
1. **AI Jason** (https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=6B29VDvPPzc) — characterizes MongoDB/document stores as "still kind of tabular," making many-to-many traversal cumbersome vs. native graph databases.
2. **Company Brain Modular RAG** (https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=NK8tTrZ3jEw) — most direct comparison: MongoDB Atlas Vector Search vs. Postgres/pgvector. MongoDB better for polymorphic JSON; Postgres better for complex permissioning, filtered vector search, and joining vectors with organizational metadata. Verdict: relational-vector hybrid more effective for company brain.
3. **Cognee** (https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Rnm2BlZU1t0) — contrasts "single database typology" (how many orgs use MongoDB vector search) with triple-store approach. Single database finds similar text but lacks structural reasoning.
4. **GraphRAG** (https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=f6pUqDeMiG0) — contrasts with "baseline RAG" (including MongoDB Atlas Vector Search) — vector similarity vs. relationship understanding.
5. **Letta/MemGPT** (https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=sgD-sw0RW78) — contrasts with "stateless" approaches using simple document stores for RAG. Argues persistent state in PostgreSQL is the true moat.

**Summary:** MongoDB is positioned as a "starting point" for simple vector search but is consistently characterized as insufficient for the structural reasoning, multi-hop traversal, temporal awareness, and complex permissioning that a true "company brain" requires. The YouTube consensus favors PostgreSQL (pgvector) for relational+vector workloads and Neo4j/Neptune for graph workloads, with file-system/Markdown approaches for coding-agent wikis.

